@jooykim Now you can get node labels from `EvaluatorDescriptor`.

example:
```java
Set<String> nodeLabelExpressions = allocatedEvaluator.getEvaluatorDescriptor().getNodeLabelExpressions();
```

@scan3 Thanks for the PR.
@motus Thanks for the review.
@motus @markusweimer @scan3's design exposes preemption as a common event for all runtimes. Are you fine with this approach? Another possibility is to add a way to expose events generically that a particular runtime can interpret; this is an approach similar to what we do in node labels.

@markusweimer Thanks a lot for your comments. I have discussed with the REEF folks in our lab and @scan3. Here's the summary.

* Adding a generic API in REEF is beneficial in that REEF developers can specify the constraints of the nodes without being aware of the APIs of each RM clients. I got the feedback from the REEF folks in SNU that it is quite annoying to use RM client APIs directly in REEF applications.
* However, I also agree that current key-value API could be misleading, and not general enough too. (in case that we support other RMs which specify node contrains in a way that cannot be expressed as the key-value map)
* I agree that the name "Scheduling Constraint" is better than "Node Labeling". @scan3 will change the name.

So, my suggestion is changing the current way of designating node constrains(key-value maps) into more general way. We can make a new interface, called `SchedulingContraint` and make the implementation classes like `YarnSchedulingConstraint` and `MesosSchedulingConstraint` for setting RM-specific constraints through their own builders. `EvaluatorRequestor` will get the `SchedulingConstraint` from `setSchedulingConstraint()` method.

@markusweimer Would you please let me know whether my answer is enough for your question and how you think about the new plan? Thanks a lot again for your comments!

This sounds much better. One concern is that we should have a generic way of adding constraints such that a Driver doesn't have to know whether it asks for node labels on YARN or Mesos. Maybe we can have something like this?

```java
public interface SchedulingConstraintBuilder{

  /**
   * Require the allocated Evaluators to be on nodes with the given label
   */
  public SchedulingConstraintBuilder requireNodeLabel(final String nodeLabel);

  // we can add more scheduling constraints supported by all runtimes here over time

  /**
   * @return the set of scheduling constraints to be passed to the EvaluatorRequestor
   */
  public SchedulingConstraint build();
```

Then, we could have specific injectable implementations for YARN, Mesos, Local, ... which have at least these methods, but can expose runtime specific constraint builders.

WDYT of this plan?

@markusweimer I like the plan.
It looks like the design's finally getting settled down. :)

@scan3 Can you update this PR to reflect the comments from @markusweimer and @DifferentSC?
